# Advanced Type Safety Patterns

## 🔒 Generic Type Constraints

### Constraint-Based Design
- **ALWAYS** use constraint-based generics instead of loose `unknown` types
- **REQUIRED**: Define base constraint interfaces for type families

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Type constraint pattern
interface WorkflowData extends Record<string, unknown> {
    readonly __workflowType?: string;
}

interface ConverterInterface<TInput extends WorkflowData, TOutput extends WorkflowData> {
    canConvert(input: WorkflowData): input is TInput;
}

// ❌ INCORRECT: Loose typing
interface ConverterInterface<TInput, TOutput> {
    canConvert(input: unknown): input is TInput; // Type predicate conflicts
}
```

## 🏷️ Type Branding and Discriminated Unions

### Mandatory Type Branding
- **REQUIRED**: All workflow data types must include `__workflowType` discriminator
- **PURPOSE**: Runtime type safety and debugging clarity

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Branded types
interface RobotaWorkflow extends WorkflowData {
    readonly __workflowType: 'RobotaWorkflowStructure';
    nodes: WorkflowNode[];
}

interface UniversalWorkflow extends WorkflowData {
    readonly __workflowType: 'UniversalWorkflowStructure';
    nodes: UniversalWorkflowNode[];
}
```

## 🎭 Facade Pattern with Type Safety

### Abstract Base Classes
- **PATTERN**: Use abstract base classes for common functionality
- **CONSTRAINT**: All base classes must use constrained generics
- **PRINCIPLE**: Hide complexity behind simple, type-safe interfaces

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Type-safe facade
export abstract class BaseConverter<TInput extends WorkflowData, TOutput extends WorkflowData>
    implements ConverterInterface<TInput, TOutput> {
    
    // Common logic with type safety
    canConvert(input: WorkflowData): input is TInput {
        return input.__workflowType === this.expectedInputType;
    }
    
    abstract readonly expectedInputType: string;
    abstract convert(input: TInput): Promise<TOutput>;
}
```

## 🚫 Type Predicate Conflict Resolution

### Solving Predicate Conflicts
- **PROBLEM**: `unknown` types cause predicate assignability issues
- **SOLUTION**: Use constraint-based approach with base interfaces

```typescript
// ❌ PROBLEMATIC: Type predicate conflict
canConvert(input: unknown): input is TInput // TInput not assignable to unknown

// ✅ SOLUTION: Constraint-based predicate
canConvert(input: WorkflowData): input is TInput // TInput extends WorkflowData
```

## 📦 Interface Segregation with Generics

### Minimal Interface Contracts
- **PRINCIPLE**: Interfaces should depend only on necessary constraints
- **PATTERN**: Use generic constraints to enforce minimal requirements

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Segregated interface
interface ValidationInterface<TData extends WorkflowData> {
    readonly dataFormat: string;
    validate(data: TData): Promise<ValidationResult>;
    canValidate(data: WorkflowData): data is TData;
}

// ❌ TOO BROAD: Coupling to specific implementations
interface ValidationInterface {
    validateUniversalWorkflow(data: UniversalWorkflow): Promise<ValidationResult>;
    validateRobotaWorkflow(data: RobotaWorkflow): Promise<ValidationResult>;
}
```

## 🔧 Type-Safe Configuration Injection

### Configuration Pattern
- **REQUIREMENT**: All configuration must be type-safe
- **PATTERN**: Use Record<string, unknown> with proper casting only when necessary

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Type-safe configuration
interface BaseModuleOptions {
    enabled?: boolean;
    logger?: SimpleLogger;
    config?: Record<string, unknown>; // Escape hatch when needed
}

// Usage with safe casting
const specificConfig = options.config as MySpecificConfig;
```

## ⚠️ Type Assertion Guidelines

### When to Use Type Assertions
- **LAST RESORT**: Only when interfacing with external, untyped data
- **PATTERN**: Prefer type guards over assertions
- **SAFETY**: Always validate before asserting

```typescript
// ✅ PREFERRED: Type guard
function isValidWorkflow(data: unknown): data is WorkflowData {
    return typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && '__workflowType' in data;
}

// ✅ ACCEPTABLE: Safe assertion with validation
if (isValidWorkflow(input)) {
    const workflow = input; // Type narrowed safely
}

// ❌ DANGEROUS: Blind assertion
const workflow = input as WorkflowData; // No validation
```

## 🚨 **Type Declaration Anti-Patterns**

### **CRITICAL**: Prevent Type Proliferation
- **NEVER** create duplicate `Record<string,` types across files
- **ALWAYS** search for existing types before creating new ones
- **REQUIRED**: Use composition over duplication

```typescript
// ❌ PROHIBITED: Type proliferation 
// File A:
interface ConfigA { [key: string]: unknown; }
// File B: 
interface ConfigB { [key: string]: any; }
// File C:
interface OptionsC { [key: string]: string | number; }

// ✅ CORRECT: Single source of truth
// common-types.ts:
type GenericConfig = Record<string, primitive | GenericConfig | GenericConfig[]>;
// All files import and extend GenericConfig
```

### **Index Signature Over-Constraint Problem**
```typescript
// ❌ PROBLEMATIC: Rigid constraints causing type conflicts
interface WorkflowData {
    [key: string]: string | number | boolean; // Breaks with Date, objects
}

// ✅ SOLUTION: Minimal constraints with TypeScript inference
interface WorkflowData {
    readonly __workflowType?: string;
    // Let TypeScript handle the rest naturally
}
```

## 🎯 Implementation Checklist

### Type Safety Requirements
- [ ] All generic interfaces use proper constraints
- [ ] All workflow types include `__workflowType` discriminator
- [ ] Type predicates use constraint-based parameters
- [ ] Abstract base classes implement facade pattern
- [ ] Configuration injection is type-safe
- [ ] No loose `unknown` or `any` types in public APIs

### Type Reuse Requirements ⚠️ **NEW**
- [ ] Search performed before creating any new type
- [ ] No duplicate `Record<string,` declarations across files
- [ ] Common base types (GenericConfig, GenericMetadata) used
- [ ] Type composition preferred over duplication
- [ ] Maximum 5-10 base types covering all use cases

### Error Prevention
- [ ] No type predicate conflicts (TInput assignable to parameter type)
- [ ] No missing discriminator properties
- [ ] No unsafe type assertions without validation
- [ ] All base interfaces properly constrained
- [ ] No index signature over-constraints causing compatibility issues